<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEAVING 'ROSEANNE' OFF THE EMMY LIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The fact that "Roseanne" was once again snubbed for a best comedy series Emmy 
nomination is good news to those of us who prefer our television comedy on the 
intelligent side ("TV Academy Is Snubbing 'Roseanne,' " July 23). 
</P>
<P>
 The success of such excellent, intelligent shows as "Frasier," "Northern 
Exposure," "Seinfeld" and "Murphy Brown" seems to indicate that once again the 
networks are aiming for our minds instead of the gutter.Keep up the good work. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN McELLIGOTT JR., Fullerton 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Regarding why the "TV Academy Is Snubbing 'Roseanne,' " the answer is in the 
mere presence of its subversive star. The woman might as well be Godzilla as 
far as the industry is concerned. From the moment Roseanne arrived in 
Hollywood, she has been very public about her disdain for the sexism, phoniness 
and political game-playing that impedes instead of encourages creativity. 
</P>
<P>
 Everyone knows that she is the driving force behind that show, and there is no 
way that they are going to acknowledge her with a producer's award. If Roseanne 
gets credit for knowing what she is doing, then maybe it's not a coincidence 
that she is hugely popular, and maybe she's on to something, and then maybe, 
just maybe, she's right, and then Hollywood would have to cop to the fact that 
most of the product we churn out is boring and uninspired with no valid excuse. 
</P>
<P>
 DOUG MOTEL, Los Angeles 
</P>
