<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOU COULDN'T SAY HE WON IN A BREEZE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Today's article, "Mitchell Makes Point in Bad Will 100," makes the statement 
that Dennis Mitchell's time was "respectable considering the stiff wind of 1.9 
meters per second in his face." 
</P>
<P>
 Silently grumbling about what quasi-socialistic forces must be at work in this 
country for it to have come to this, I set about converting this to American 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
 My calculation went as follows: 
</P>
<P>
 -- 1.9 meters per second times 3,600 seconds per hour equals 6,840 meters per 
hour. 
</P>
<P>
 -- At 1,625 meters per mile, divide 6,840 by 1,625 to get 4.21 miles per hour. 
</P>
<P>
 Is this the "stiff wind" your article refers to? Why don't we stick to 
American from now on in the sports page? 
</P>
<P>
 T. LOUIS FILLIGER 
</P>
<P>
 San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
