<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; ANGELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rod Carew, Angel hitting coach, said he would have bunted to break up Rogers' 
perfect game and doesn't understand why no one attempted a bunt Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 "A base hit is a base hit," Carew said."If a guy's getting you out, I'd drop 
one down. Even if I'm the last hitter up, I'm trying to break it up any way I 
can." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Ranger Manager Kevin Kennedy: "If somebody had bunted, I would have shot 
him." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Rogers' perfect game was only the second pitched in the first year of a 
ballpark. The Philadelphia Phillies' Jim Bunning pitched one in 1964 at Shea 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 There have been only seven no-hitters pitched in first-year ballparks, the 
last thrown by Nolan Ryan on May 15, 1973 at Royals Stadium in Kansas City. BOB 
NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA073094-0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 065334 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
