<HEADLINE>
<P>
TORY AUTHOR ARCHER CLEARED IN INSIDER-TRADE INVESTIGATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Best-selling novelist and Conservative politician Jeffrey Archer declared 
Friday that he is "grateful to have been exonerated" after Britain's Department 
of Trade and Industry cleared him of any suspicion of insider trading in stock 
shares. 
</P>
<P>
 The department announced that Archer was under investigation just weeks before 
a Cabinet reshuffle by Prime Minister John Major.Archer had been widely 
expected to receive a government post or the Conservative Party chairmanship, 
but the announcement foreclosed his chances. 
</P>
<P>
 Trade and Industry Minister Michael Heseltine received the investigators' 
report a day before last week's Cabinet changes but declined to disclose the 
findings. 
</P>
<P>
 Heseltine, a political rival of Archer's, has been criticized for making the 
investigation public in the first place and then not immediately revealing that 
Archer had been exonerated. 
</P>
<P>
 Some observers speculated that Archer was the victim of political "dirty 
tricks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA073094-0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 065370 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 30, 1994, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 14; Column 1; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
518 words 
</P>
