<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; COUNCILMAN WON'T SEEK REELECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFFREY BEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Councilman Jeff Vasquez said Friday that he will not be running for a 
second term. 
</P>
<P>
 The 37-year-old Vasquez, who owns a photography and video business, said he 
felt it was time to let someone else seek a seat on the council. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think one of the things I was able to bring to the council was a fresh 
perspective and the vigor to make changes to the city," Vasquez said. 
</P>
<P>
 "One of the things wrong with government is that some people stay in it too 
long." 
</P>
<P>
 Vasquez said he was proud to help make City Hall more responsive to residents 
and make decisions from the voters' perspective. 
</P>
<P>
 Vasquez becomes the second incumbent not to seek reelection. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, Councilman Gary L. Hausdorfer said he would not be running again. 
</P>
<P>
 Three seats are up for election in November. Only incumbent Gil Jones has 
filed nomination papers. 
</P>
<P>
 Six people have obtained nomination papers as of Friday, according to City 
Clerk Cheryl Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
 If an incumbent doesn't file by the Aug. 12 deadline, the filing period is 
extended to Aug. 17, Johnson said. JEFFREY BEAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
