<DOCID> 065480 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 30, 1994, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 1; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
137 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: THE INCREDIBLE SHRINKING VAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For the corporate executive who is overwhelmed and stressed out -- and can 
afford to pay $175 an hour for help -- two New York psychologists offer therapy 
to go. 
</P>
<P>
 "We thought up the idea of coming to the client and using every moment of time 
while in transit," said psychologist Ursula Strauss.She started Mobile 
Psychological Services in April with partner Shelley Lennox. 
</P>
<P>
 Before, an executive might stop for a martini after work. "Now it's life on 
the move," Strauss said. "Instead of the martini, they're getting intense 
therapy." 
</P>
<P>
 A fully equipped but unmarked van comes to the executive's office. Many execs 
receive treatment on the way to a business meeting or to the airport or 
commuting home.  
</P>
<P>
 "We tell the driver to keep at a slow pace, stay in the right-hand lane, avoid 
rapid turns," Strauss said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
